Xanta had found, secretly hording the collection, the bones of Darkmask. From a necromancer of high renown, she gained his skull, not asking any more questions than neccessary, knowing the feel of Darkmask's skull, as she'd watched him so long, using every seduction in the book against the necromancer, swallowing her own pride and humility. She had waited too long, she feared, too long had she gone without saying what she felt. She could only hope she had enough of his bones to work the magic, and she knew she'd feel drained when she did so. Darkmask was worth this though, a moment of loss, an hour of pain, a week of grief, for him, yes. While Xanta had only enough mastery of her cleric art to the 59th season, she pleaded to the Goddess Tunare, that this ressurection would work. She felt she was too late, but hoped, and meditated.<br>
<br>
Weaving her hands through the air, she began the old way, the ways before her quest for the Water Sprinkler. This must be done right, she knew. She began the old incantation, and realized, there must be more. She slipped into a trance, recalling where she'd first seen him, how he'd touched her and he did not know, the time the rogue Kealii dragged his battered body to her in Karnor's Castle, and she'd brought him back then, her heart beating so fast against her ribcage, she thought surely he could hear her. How she had fallen in love with him, after hearing his name echoed in the cleric halls in Felewithe, whispered by another sister cleric, who'd succumbed to the lure of evil, using her power in twisted ways. These things she confessed, as she thought of the loss of him, reworking an old magic, into something of her own.<br>
<br>
Pulling a small dagger from her bags, this she'd found once in Befallen, the only dagger she could ever hope to use to cut herself, she opened for a moment her tunic, and slashed at her chest, at her heart. Cringing, she knew this would never heal, as it was her own sacrifice. Nothing deep, but she needed her own life blood for this, too long had she waited for him. She whispered, "May my life be yours, I am your servant and your mistress, I will follow you, and may you follow me, my heart beats for you, may yours beat for me. I give you this, my essence, my soul. For without you there is no forever, without you, I wish to join you as bones abused by both necromancer and shadowknight, without you, I forsake life." Tears streamed down her cheeks, as she continued. "Never will I be silent again, but nor do I wish for you to know that I give so much to you... May my love be both loud and silent, may you feel me within you, and around you, and through you... Darkmask, I love you... F O R E V E R...." <br>
<br>
She flung her head back to the sky, howling this last word, hearing it echo through the hills. She hoped with her whole self that this would be enough, that she might be enough, and the one to ressurect him. Feeling the final rush of light, she stretched out her hands, hoped one last time, her body shaking with both hope and sorrow, and from her fingers let flow the blue light.<br>
<br>
Slowly, so slowly, the bones came together, forming a skeleton. She feared for a moment she'd gone too far, and somehow become a necromancer, till she began to see his body flicker into sight, as she had known him. As his aura formed around him, she began to work a celetial elixir, feeling the pulse of her heart behind it, and touched his flickering self, letting both the light and her emotion pulse into him. She watched as his heart began to beat, and he looked up at her, in wonderment, in amazement. His eyes lit up, as if he truly saw her, for the first time. She watched as he became solid, and from her bags, pulled all his old things, that she'd managed to find. His robe, his staff, a mug, a wreath. This were trinkets of memory only, no value anymore, not with what he'd had. Perhaps a banker still kept a key to his holdings, bank customers going long periods of time without looking in their vaults. However, for now, this was inconsequential. <br>
<br>
He was alive. Breathing, his heart beating, his eyes flashing, taking all things in around him, and Darkmask looked at Xanta.<br>
<br>
Helping him rise up into a sitting position, she stepped back, relishing the closeness, and his now warmth, so opposite from the chill of his bones. She wrapped a blanket round him, and brought him his things. As he dressed, she spoke.<br>
<br>
"Darkmask," she whispered. "I've brought you back. I hope I've not intruded on your sleep. My love."<br>
<br>
Darkmask cocked his head a bit at the "my love", but waited for Xanta to say more. Seeing as this was all, he pondered for a moment while he finished dressed.<br>
<br>
She'd added the last bit as a confession, and she bit her lip. She was a bit afraid, that after all this, he'd turn away from her. He sensed this, and started to speak, then motioned for a drink. Pulling several water flasks from her bags, Xanta brought them to him.<br>
<br>
"It has been a long time, Xanta, too long."<br>
<br>
"Aye, I am so sorry, Darkmask, I didn't know.. I only knew of your passing, but... that was all. No one told me, no one. I knew only after it was too late."<br>
<br>
"But was it too late, my dear? Was it?"<br>
<br>
Xanta blushed furiously, and again with the tears, forming and coursing down her cheek. "It was," she confessed.<br>
<br>
Darkmask looked amazed. "You... how... why did you..."<br>
<br>
Looking at the ground for a moment, she replied, "Because for too long I have been silent, and," she fidgeted a moment, then rose her eyes and looked at him, "I have loved you. And I always will."<br>
<br>
She lowered herself to him, sitting on her knees in front of him, and forgetting her place, and not caring where it was, reached for his face. With a hand, she ran her fingers over his jaw, feeling his fine lines. She ran her thumb over one of his eyebrows, and could tell he'd frowned for much time. She mimicked this movement with her other hand, and then ran her fingers through his hair, drew his face close to her, and kissed him, her lips catching his lower lip, drawing his mouth into hers, feeling him return the kiss.<br>
